Rating: 4
Excellent recipe. Easy to prepare, not a lot of ingredients. Really good flavor combinations. Loved the apricots with the cherries, and a hint of almond. Cobbler dough is rich but still light. Make sure you use a dish with high enough sides so it doesn't bubble over. You need the right ratio of dough to fruit. This will become a standby.

Rating: 4
Icut back on the sugar to only 1/2 cup because my cherries were sweet. I also only used 2 tbs of conrstarch insteadh of 3. It was very good (even though I wish I had a cherry pitter). The combination of the apricots and the berries was very good. I added some fresh currants I had for tartness. It is true the topping soaks up a lot of the juice. I did not have spillage problems but I did use a pan with high sides - a metal one instead of a glass one.

Rating: 4
Got rave reviews from my customers. In one batch I used frozen sweet cherries (straight from the bag); in the other, canned. Frozen is better. This crust is wonderful, very old- fashioned. I used whipping cream, no buttermilk. Great recipe!

Rating: 4
This was fabulous! The almond and cherry aroma was sensational and the fruit colors made a beautiful presentation. We enjoyed it immensely!!!

Rating: 4
I have already made this dish three times this summer and it was a huge hit every time! Last time substituted peaches for apricots and was still delicious!

Rating: 1
I gave this cobbler one star as the definition was "just so-so" it's not horrible or offensive, but it is nothing to write home about either! I think it was a waste of delicious fruit. I won't be making this again. I made it in two, deeper pans per previous recommendations, and there was no bubbling over. However, here was also no fruit and juice. There is too much cornstarch in this recipe. I even had extra fruit, which was ripe and juicy and the finished product was fruit flavored biscuits. I would recommend if you want to make this, halve the biscuit portion.

Rating: 3
I used fresh Bing cherries and frozen peach slices. I would follow one person's suggestion: add less sugar (1/2c) to the filling and maybe some lemon zest to the topping. The biscuit topping came out really well. I cooked the fruit along with my chicken dinner and cooked the topping while we were eating dinner. Timing worked beautifully.

Rating: 4
I made this for a backyard barbecue and my guests raved -- much better than serving boring old strawberry shortcake. I made it exactly as directed. The buttermilk biscuit topping was very tasty. I placed the baking dish on a foil-lined cookie sheet because it did run over the sides.

Rating: 3
This was a great cobbler. I made it with cherries straight off the tree and some not-quite-ripe apricots, and it turned out fine. It bubbled over, as others mentioned, making me wish I had a taller pan or hadn't filled it so full.

